'''Lunar distance''' ('''LD''' or <math display="inline"> \Delta_{\oplus L}</math>), also called '''Earth–Moon distance''', '''Earth–Moon characteristic distance''', or '''distance to the Moon''', is a [[unit of measure]] in [[astronomy]]. It is the average distance from the center of [[Earth]] to the center of the [[Moon]]. More technically, it is the mean [[semi-major axis]] of the geocentric [[orbit of the Moon|lunar orbit]]. It may also refer to the time-averaged distance between the centers of the Earth and the Moon, or less commonly, the instantaneous Earth–Moon distance. The lunar distance is approximately {{val|400000|u=km}}, or a quarter of a million miles.

The mean semi-major axis has a value of {{convert|384402|km|mi|abbr=on}}.{{r|Apache Point}} The time-averaged distance between Earth and Moon centers is {{convert|385000.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}. The actual distance varies over the course of the [[orbit of the Moon]], from {{convert|356500|km|mi|abbr=on}} at the [[perigee]] to {{convert|406700|km|mi|abbr=on}} at [[apogee]], resulting in a differential range of {{convert|50200|km|mi|abbr=on}}.{{r|millimeter challenge}}

Lunar distance is commonly used to express the distance to [[near-Earth object]] encounters.{{r|NEO}} Lunar distance is also an important astronomical datum; the precision of this measurement to a few parts in a trillion has implications for testing gravitational theories such as [[general relativity]],{{r|Relativity}} and for refining other astronomical values such as [[Earth mass]],{{r|moonbounce}} [[Earth radius]],{{r|Fischer}} and Earth's rotation.{{r|LLR}} The measurement is also useful in characterizing the [[lunar radius]], the [[Solar mass|mass of the Sun]] and the [[Astronomical unit|distance to the Sun]].

Millimeter-[[Accuracy and precision|precision]] measurements of the lunar distance are made by measuring the time taken for light to travel between [[LIDAR]] stations on the Earth and [[retroreflector]]s placed on the Moon. The Moon is spiraling away from the Earth at an average rate of {{convert|3.8|cm|in|abbr=on}} per year, as detected by the [[Lunar Laser Ranging Experiment]].{{r|drift1|drift2|drift3}}

