== Variation ==
The instantaneous lunar distance is constantly changing. In fact the true distance between the Moon and Earth can change as quickly as {{val|75|u=meters per second}},{{r|millimeter challenge}} or more than {{val|1000|u=km}} in just 6 hours, due to its non-circular orbit.{{r|Zuluaga}} There are other effects that also influence the lunar distance. Some factors are described in this section.

=== Perturbations and eccentricity ===
The distance to the Moon can be measured to an accuracy of {{val|2|u=mm}} over a 1-hour sampling period,{{r|APOLLO Analysis}} which results in an overall uncertainty of {{val|2|–|3|u=cm}} for the average distance. However, due to [[Orbit of the Moon|its elliptical orbit]] with varying eccentricity, the instantaneous distance varies with monthly periodicity. Furthermore, the distance is perturbed by the gravitational effects of various astronomical bodies – most significantly the Sun and less so Jupiter. Other forces responsible for minute perturbations are: gravitational attraction to other planets in the solar system and to asteroids; tidal forces; and relativistic effects.{{r|integration}} The effect of [[Yarkovsky effect|radiation pressure]] from the Sun contributes an amount of ±{{val|3.6|u=mm}} to the lunar distance.{{r|APOLLO Analysis}}

Although the instantaneous uncertainty is sub-millimeter, the measured lunar distance can change by more than {{val|21000|u=km}} from the mean value throughout a typical month. These perturbations are well understood{{r|DE431}} and the lunar distance can be accurately modeled over thousands of years.{{r|integration}}

[[File:Moon-Earth distance, Moon phases.gif|thumb|upright=3|left|The Moon's distance from the [[Earth]] and [[Lunar phase|Moon phases]] in 2014.<br>Moon phases: 0 (1) – [[new moon]], 0.25 – first quarter, 0.5 – [[full moon]], 0.75 – last quarter.]]
[[File:Moon's orbit - Variation of distance en.png|thumb|right|upright=1.28|Variation of the distance between the centers of the [[Moon]] and the [[Earth]] over 700 days.]]
